00:00:02.590 --> 00:00:04.410
NINA: Thank you all for coming.

00:00:04.410 --> 00:00:05.370
My name is Nina.

00:00:05.370 --> 00:00:10.440
And today we have Rohan Dixit to
present Engineering Calm Sensor

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:13.250
Driven Meditation technology
as part of the Talks

00:00:13.250 --> 00:00:15.940
at Google series brought
to you by gPause,

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:18.240
a community of
mindfulness practices

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:20.750
for well being change at Google.

00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:23.360
The last 10 years have
seen the growing acceptance

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:26.710
of mindfulness meditation
in mainstream science.

00:00:26.710 --> 00:00:28.870
Hundreds of studies
have now demonstrated

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:32.280
quantifiable physiological
effects of meditation

00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:36.410
on heart rhythms, stress,
immune response, and more.

00:00:36.410 --> 00:00:38.240
In fact, it appears
the brain itself

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:41.010
changes both during
the act of meditation,

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:43.670
as well as after
repeated practice.

00:00:43.670 --> 00:00:45.670
We'll show you the
brainwave, heartbeat,

00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:47.690
and breath sensors
that can help you track

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:49.720
your mind during your day.

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:52.780
For example, breathing patterns
are correlated with stress.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:55.260
And, in fact, many
forms of meditation

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:57.750
encourage watching
of the breath.

00:00:57.750 --> 00:01:00.600
A wearable respiration sensor
that gives you feedback

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.330
when you're stressed can
be imagined as a technology

00:01:03.330 --> 00:01:06.170
assisted meditation practice.

00:01:06.170 --> 00:01:08.480
The coming ubiquity
of wearable sensors

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:10.880
make opportunities
for calm engineering

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:13.770
like this potentially
quite common.

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:16.480
We'll show you the state
of the field today.

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:19.410
Rohan Dixit is a
founder at BrainBot

00:01:19.410 --> 00:01:21.770
and a former
neuroimaging researcher

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:27.690
at the Harvard MIT MGH Martino
Center and Stanford University.

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:30.800
In a search for the ultimate
meaning of life, the universe,

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:33.450
and everything,
Rohan quit his job

00:01:33.450 --> 00:01:35.730
and bought a one-way
ticket to the Himalayas

00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:38.410
where he lived with
Tibetan monks for a year

00:01:38.410 --> 00:01:41.530
and recorded their brain
waves during meditation.

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:43.610
This eventually led
to a meditation app

00:01:43.610 --> 00:01:46.960
that uses a brain waves sensor
as well as a flower that blooms

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:48.940
with your calm brain waves.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:50.800
This summer and
fall, Rohan will be

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:53.890
creating a variety of
large art installations

00:01:53.890 --> 00:01:57.010
that react to your
relaxed heartbeat,

00:01:57.010 --> 00:01:59.670
including a garden,
a 15 feet tall metal

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:02.480
lotuses, and huge
murals that encourage

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:04.970
heart syncing between people.

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:06.720
I'm thrilled to
present to you today

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:10.488
my former classmate and dear
friend of 10 years, Rohan.

