You can imagine that sensors
are something that's pretty new,

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:34.280
especially wearable
sensors, whereas meditation

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.049
is something that's pretty
ancient and pretty old.

00:02:37.049 --> 00:02:38.840
So it's an interesting
kind of intersection

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:40.307
to be playing with.

00:02:40.307 --> 00:02:42.640
And I want to talk a little
bit about the companies that

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.660
are in the space now, the
sensors that are already

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:46.951
out there, and a little bit
about what we're working on

00:02:46.951 --> 00:02:48.350
now.

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:50.810
I'll try to keep it
short so that we have

00:02:50.810 --> 00:02:54.100
a lot of time for questions.

00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:55.790
So like Nina was
saying, my background

00:02:55.790 --> 00:02:57.890
is actually in neuroimaging.

00:02:57.890 --> 00:03:01.540
And I started kind of
studying the C-word.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:05.630
So the C-word in neuroscience
is Consciousness, actually.

00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:08.580
And it's been hard
for many years--

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:10.520
actually, decades-- to
study consciousness.

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:12.185
It's kind of a taboo
subject, right?

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:17.472
So the way that we do that
in the clinical context

00:03:17.472 --> 00:03:18.846
and in neuroscience
in general is

00:03:18.846 --> 00:03:21.290
to study things that
are very, very concrete.

00:03:21.290 --> 00:03:23.560
Alterations in consciousness
like, for example,

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:24.485
people in a coma.

00:03:24.485 --> 00:03:26.110
You can imagine that
somebody in a coma

00:03:26.110 --> 00:03:28.000
has some degree
of consciousness.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.610
You can poke them
or have some kind

00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:31.960
of basic reflexes still intact.

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:34.920
But their consciousness, their
sort of awareness on some level

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:35.720
is gone.

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:38.200
So that's kind of a
window, an insight,

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:40.660
into what consciousness is.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:42.914
So we study people
who are in comas.

00:03:42.914 --> 00:03:45.330
We've studied people who were
under deep anesthesia, which

00:03:45.330 --> 00:03:47.250
is a similar kind of situation.

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:50.320
We have people who had
epilepsy-- temporal lobe

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:53.720
epilepsy-- and they tend to have
altered states of consciousness

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:55.302
during their seizures.

00:03:55.302 --> 00:03:57.010
So those are three
kind of short examples

00:03:57.010 --> 00:03:58.970
of ways of studying
consciousness

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:01.660
that exist already in
the neuroscience world.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:04.590
But eventually I ended up in
Sara Lazar's lab at Harvard

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:08.580
studying people who
meditate and their brain.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:10.720
And so you can see
here on the screen

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:13.430
this is a monk who has a whole
bunch of sensors on his head.

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:17.061
Those are called EEG sensors or
electroencephalography sensors.

00:04:17.061 --> 00:04:18.519
And basically what
they're doing is

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:19.893
measuring the
electrical activity

00:04:19.893 --> 00:04:23.100
of the brain in real time
while the monk does things.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:27.620
So you can imagine asking
the monk to meditate

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:29.650
and recording the brain
waves before and after

00:04:29.650 --> 00:04:32.140
and seeing what changes
actually happen.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:35.200
And it turns out that
the brain actually

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:36.610
does change during meditation.

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:39.440
Both over the short term
and kind of the long term.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:41.760
So with these sensors,
you're able to pick up

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.920
on these changes that are
happening structurally and also

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:48.542
the changes that are
happening in real time.

00:04:48.542 --> 00:04:50.750
So why is it that you might
want to study meditation?

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:52.541
Meditation is kind of
a hokey thing, right?

00:04:52.541 --> 00:04:55.760
It's kind of a woo-woo
or magical in a way.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.010
But the practices themselves
are actually quite simple

00:05:01.010 --> 00:05:05.950
and really kind of boil down to
attentional training and self

00:05:05.950 --> 00:05:07.050
inquiry in a way.

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:10.560
So meditation often is
associated with the East,

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:13.000
but I think this is kind
of an ancient trend.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.800
The idea of self
knowledge and self inquiry

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:17.110
was something that
Socrates was really into.

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:17.744
Know thyself.

00:05:17.744 --> 00:05:20.160
And I think that's the basis
for a lot of forms of therapy

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:21.230
as well today.

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:23.820
Kind of having self awareness
I think is how all of us

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:25.114
kind of grow as people.

00:05:25.114 --> 00:05:26.780
The ability to
introspect into yourself,

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:28.446
to see yourself in
different situations,

00:05:28.446 --> 00:05:32.030
and to understand how you
react to stressors in the world

00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:33.690
actually allows you to grow.

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.040
And meditation actually
in part is that.

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:38.320
It's building the ability
to kind of look inwards,

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.550
to see your own body,
to see your own mind,

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:46.200
and to watch yourself
with sustained attention

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:48.047
over the course of your life.

00:05:48.047 --> 00:05:50.130
So it turns out that just
like any other practice,

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:52.507
for example, learning
juggling, if you

00:05:52.507 --> 00:05:54.090
look at people who
learn juggling over

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:56.590
the course of three
to eight weeks

00:05:56.590 --> 00:05:58.290
you kind of see
that there are areas

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:00.790
in the brain like in the motor
cortex that actually thicken.

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:02.290
That is just called
neuroplasticity.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:04.510
It just seems be the case
that the brain actually

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:08.715
responds and grows in response
to repeated activities.

00:06:08.715 --> 00:06:10.340
The same thing is
true with meditation.

00:06:10.340 --> 00:06:11.839
And so what we were
doing in the lab

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:13.030
was basically studying that.

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:15.479
Trying to characterize how the
brain is actually changing.

00:06:15.479 --> 00:06:17.020
We found a lot of
interesting things.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:19.680
For example, it appears that
in as little as eight weeks

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.240
you can have measurable
changes in the brain in areas

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:26.770
that are associated with sense
of self and also empathy.

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:30.700
Those are two aspects
of personality

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:34.680
that oftentimes are interesting
to play with and to develop.

00:06:37.650 --> 00:06:41.290
So that was my life as
a researcher in a lab.

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:41.970
And I love it.

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:42.990
I love research.

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:45.020
And I'm kind of a nerd about it.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:48.760
But I found myself as we
were studying meditation

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:52.924
realizing that it was actually
a pretty beneficial thing.

00:06:52.924 --> 00:06:55.340
It seemed like the monks in
the long term meditation study

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:57.940
tended to be happier
people, just more relaxed.

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:00.880
And I kind of wanted
that for myself,

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:02.570
although I didn't
really feel it.

00:07:02.570 --> 00:07:04.809
So I decided eventually
to follow those monks

00:07:04.809 --> 00:07:06.350
that we were studying
in the lab back

00:07:06.350 --> 00:07:08.300
to the Himalayas
where they lived

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:10.915
to try to understand what
meditation actually was

00:07:10.915 --> 00:07:12.980
and to do it for myself.

00:07:12.980 --> 00:07:17.650
And because I am a nerd, I took
a bunch of brain wave equipment

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:19.420
with me to try to
measure their brains.

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:21.200
I thought I could
make a device that

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.600
would help me learn to
meditate without any

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:27.240
of the kind of
interface of words.

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:29.550
When you try to explain how
to do something to somebody

00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:32.010
you can only use words to
really describe what you mean.

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:33.840
But the advantage
of using sensors

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:36.130
is that you can
actually map what's

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:38.650
happening in someone's body to
what's happening in your body

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:41.035
without the crutch of language.

00:07:41.035 --> 00:07:41.910
So that was the idea.

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:43.930
I took a bunch of brain
wave sensors with me.

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:46.110
And I spent, as Nina was
saying, almost a year

00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:48.910
traveling around through India
going to these monasteries that

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:51.410
are at the top of the Himalayan
mountains and meeting theses

00:07:51.410 --> 00:07:52.270
monks.

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:54.020
These monks are really
interesting people.

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:57.910
I could probably tell you
stories for days about them.

00:07:57.910 --> 00:08:00.290
But what kind of
came out of that was,

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.140
one, a deeper sense
for myself personally

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:05.165
of just what meditation was
and what it could do to you.

00:08:05.165 --> 00:08:07.540
These people are really, really
nice and really friendly.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:11.320
And I think some of that stems
in part from their practices.

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:14.740
And, two, it kind
of led to this app.

00:08:17.671 --> 00:08:20.170
So when I came back from India,
some friends and I were kind

00:08:20.170 --> 00:08:22.840
of looking at the data and we
realized that with a little bit

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:24.920
of machine learning you can kind
of pick out when somebody is

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:26.540
meditating and
when they weren't.

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:29.929
So we sort of applied the state
of the art in neuroscience

00:08:29.929 --> 00:08:31.470
with a little bit
of machine learning

00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:35.370
to basically interface with a
commercially available headset.

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:36.659
This thing is about $100.

00:08:36.659 --> 00:08:38.460
It's the NeuroSky.

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:40.789
And help people
learn to meditate

00:08:40.789 --> 00:08:43.360
with a virtual
meditation instructor.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:46.300
So this app is in
the Apple App Store.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:49.110
I felt a little bit embarrassed
not having an Android app

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:50.762
coming to Google.

00:08:50.762 --> 00:08:53.150
But soon hopefully.

00:08:53.150 --> 00:08:55.290
And it kind of does
some interesting things.

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:57.970
So one of them is
just habit design,

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:00.710
which is really boring and
simple, but actually really

00:09:00.710 --> 00:09:01.237
important.

00:09:01.237 --> 00:09:03.320
I don't know if any of you
have tried to meditate.

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:05.927
I've tried and
failed so many times.

00:09:05.927 --> 00:09:06.760
It's out of control.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:09.200
And part of that is just
the ability to build a habit

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:11.110
and to do it repeatedly.

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:12.610
So some of what the
app does is just

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:17.000
simple kind of like this flower,
this plant grows in real time.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.059
And your goal is to kind of
keep it alive like a Tamagotchi.

00:09:20.059 --> 00:09:22.350
I don't know if you guys are
old enough or young enough

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:24.426
to remember what that is.

00:09:24.426 --> 00:09:26.990
But basically it's
like a little device

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:28.300
that you keep in your pocket.

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:29.150
And it was like a
little creature.

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:31.240
You had to feed it and make
sure it was healthy and happy.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:32.781
And so this is kind
of the same idea.

00:09:32.781 --> 00:09:36.620
This is a plant you keep
alive with your meditation.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:39.120
One of the cool
things that we were

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.666
able to build in with
the brain wave sensor

00:09:41.666 --> 00:09:43.165
was this kind of
realtime feedback--

00:09:43.165 --> 00:09:45.495
the virtual mediation
instructor I was talking about.

00:09:45.495 --> 00:09:47.870
So in real time we're kind of
looking at your brain waves

00:09:47.870 --> 00:09:49.770
and we're analyzing them.

00:09:49.770 --> 00:09:53.000
And when the app kind of
detects that your mind starts

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.400
to wander, it actually can give
you a short feedback queue.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.852
So this is a fun kind of example
of how that might happen.

