when you're meditating and
using that as a signal to bloom

00:11:18.070 --> 00:11:20.017
this physical flower
that sits on your desk.

00:11:20.017 --> 00:11:21.850
Over time that flower
starts to close again,

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:25.000
and that just acts as
a reminder to meditate.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.360
So that's another kind of
fun project you can do.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:29.696
It's very simple now
with these sensors

00:11:29.696 --> 00:11:31.570
and with a little bit
of a single processing.

00:11:35.190 --> 00:11:38.050
So I wanted to talk a little bit
about some of the sensors that

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:38.760
are out there.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:41.170
We're talking about
engineering calm and sensor

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:43.450
driven meditation technology.

00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:46.749
So I wanted to introduce
you to some of the, I think,

00:11:46.749 --> 00:11:48.540
cutting edge and best
in class sensors that

00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:50.022
are out there today.

00:11:50.022 --> 00:11:51.480
So this sensor is
called the Spire.

00:11:51.480 --> 00:11:54.300
You can pre-order
it I believe now.

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:56.370
And they should start
shipping in the fall.

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:58.810
But the Spire is basically
a respiration sensor.

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:01.930
So essentially what it does is
it kind of clips into your belt

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:04.600
or into your bra, and
there's a little flex sensor

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:06.260
kind of built inside.

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:08.900
And as you breathe the
Spire recognizes that you're

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:12.514
breathing and kind of
analyzes that on your phone,

00:12:12.514 --> 00:12:14.430
and gives you a feedback
signal and determines

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:17.790
that your breathing
pattern seems stressed out.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:19.960
So you can imagine that
your body is all connected.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:21.460
Your brain, your
heart, your breath.

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:23.730
These things are all
intimately linked in some way.

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:25.930
And so almost like
a hologram, if you

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:29.410
look at any piece of your
body or any kind of aspect,

00:12:29.410 --> 00:12:32.110
any biosignal, you can see
reflections of other signals,

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:32.620
as well.

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:36.210
And so by analyzing the
breath, the people at Spire

00:12:36.210 --> 00:12:38.970
have been able to find
a way to sort of get

00:12:38.970 --> 00:12:42.125
at when you're stressed out and
the phone kind of buzzes you

00:12:42.125 --> 00:12:44.500
when it determines that you're
either holding your breath

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:47.757
or the breath is
sort of indicative of

00:12:47.757 --> 00:12:50.170
a stressed or frustrated state.

00:12:50.170 --> 00:12:52.420
We actually hooked
this up to the Lotus

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:54.670
a couple weeks ago at a
consciousness hacking meeting,

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:57.600
which is meet up that
happens in San Francisco

00:12:57.600 --> 00:12:59.120
about every month.

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:00.865
And this is the emWave.

00:13:00.865 --> 00:13:03.090
So we just talked
about the breath.

00:13:03.090 --> 00:13:05.627
The Spire looks at respiration.

00:13:05.627 --> 00:13:08.210
The emWave is a product that's
been around for about 10 years.

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.620
And I think it's
probably the best

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:14.240
kind of heart rate
or heart derived

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:15.777
meditation device out there.

00:13:15.777 --> 00:13:18.110
So I just want to kind of
talk you through how it works.

00:13:18.110 --> 00:13:20.140
You can kind of see based
on the screen there's

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:22.700
like a little box and a clip.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:25.150
That clip essentially
goes on to your ear lobe.

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:27.930
And what it's doing
is measuring your HRV.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:30.150
So your HRV is Heart
Rate Variability.

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:32.994
It's a signal that's embedded
inside of your heart rhythm.

00:13:32.994 --> 00:13:34.410
It's kind of an
interesting thing.

00:13:34.410 --> 00:13:37.240
And you can probably kind of
test this as you sit here.

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:40.630
When you're relatively
relaxed and you breathe in,

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:42.122
your heartbeat actually goes up.

00:13:42.122 --> 00:13:44.080
People often have this
idea that your heartbeat

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:45.450
is pretty stable.

00:13:45.450 --> 00:13:46.409
It's actually not true.

00:13:46.409 --> 00:13:48.699
Your heartbeat is constantly
kind of going up and down.

00:13:48.699 --> 00:13:51.260
And the way that it works is
on inhale your heartbeat rises

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:52.260
a little bit.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:54.360
You can kind of test, right?

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:56.547
And on exhale your heart
beat kind of drops.

00:13:56.547 --> 00:13:58.630
So if you graph that over
time, what you're seeing

00:13:58.630 --> 00:14:01.910
is basically on an inhale your
heartbeat goes up and an exhale

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:02.490
it goes down.

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:04.370
And that kind of
sinusoidal rhythm

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:08.290
is what the emWave uses
to give you feedback

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:09.631
as to when you're relaxed.

00:14:09.631 --> 00:14:11.130
If you're not very
relaxed or you're

00:14:11.130 --> 00:14:13.200
kind of frustrated or
tense, you're not actually

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:16.050
able to elicit that sinusoidal
wave when you breath in

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:17.276
and breath out.

00:14:17.276 --> 00:14:18.650
The way that the
emWave does that

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:22.130
is with a series of LEDs that
are on the side of this device.

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:25.300
Basically as you breath in, the
LEDs go up, as you breath in,

00:14:25.300 --> 00:14:26.460
they go down.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:30.290
And you just kind of look
at that and try to relax,

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:33.560
elicit that wave, which,
of course, is correlated

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:36.670
with your body actually
feeling less tense,

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:40.040
less stressed, and relaxed.

00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:41.680
So we kind of
riffed on that idea,

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:44.010
the idea of heart
rate variability

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:46.790
or this kind of stress
signal inside of the heart

00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:49.531
beat in this big installation
we're doing over the summer.

00:14:49.531 --> 00:14:51.030
So this is happening
at Burning Man.

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:54.354
We got a grant from them to
do a big art installation.

00:14:54.354 --> 00:14:56.020
As Nina was saying,
there are these kind

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:57.570
of these 15 foot tall lotuses.

00:14:57.570 --> 00:14:59.852
And this is a mockup
and a rendering.

00:14:59.852 --> 00:15:01.685
We're building it now
out in American Steel.

00:15:01.685 --> 00:15:05.270
If anybody wants to help, you're
more than welcome to swing by.

00:15:05.270 --> 00:15:07.680
But basically the way that
this installation works

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:10.709
is by measuring people's HRV,
or Heart Rate Variability,

00:15:10.709 --> 00:15:12.500
that kind of breathing
in and breathing out

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:16.450
signal of relaxation and
kind of correlating that

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:19.650
to the brightness of
a 15 foot tall Lotus

00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:21.192
in the middle of the desert.

00:15:21.192 --> 00:15:22.150
Now, it's not just one.

00:15:22.150 --> 00:15:24.162
Like with the emWave
it's a single device.

00:15:24.162 --> 00:15:25.620
But the way that
this works is more

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:28.530
of an interactive,
collaborative thing.

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:32.090
So why would you want to have
the HRV measured, the Heart

00:15:32.090 --> 00:15:35.090
Rate Variability measured for
different people in a group

00:15:35.090 --> 00:15:35.740
setting?

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:38.077
It turns out there was
some research in 2013

00:15:38.077 --> 00:15:39.160
that came out of UC Davis.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:40.243
It was really interesting.

00:15:40.243 --> 00:15:42.570
So I read this and I got
of course very excited

00:15:42.570 --> 00:15:44.200
because I'm a nerd
and I get excited

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:45.630
about this kind of stuff.

00:15:45.630 --> 00:15:48.250
And what it kind of
showed was that people

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:51.620
who are in a long term
relationship for a year

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:54.470
or more, if you put them
across from their partner

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:56.970
and just kind of have them stare
into their partner's eyes--

00:15:56.970 --> 00:15:59.070
no talking allowed
for three minutes.

00:15:59.070 --> 00:16:01.935
It's kind of a long time.

00:16:01.935 --> 00:16:03.310
It's kind of crazy,
but if you're

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:06.380
measuring their heart rate,
they actually start to sync up.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:08.600
The Heart Rate Variability
of both of these people

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:10.607
starts to align and sync.

00:16:10.607 --> 00:16:12.190
And if you switch
that out to somebody

00:16:12.190 --> 00:16:15.260
in the waiting room who is a
member of another couple-- so

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:18.600
two strangers-- that
syncing doesn't happen.

00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:21.564
So the interpretation
that the researchers had

00:16:21.564 --> 00:16:23.480
was that the ability to
empathize with someone

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:26.160
allows you to somehow have these
subconscious cues that actually

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:28.530
lets you sync with other people.

00:16:28.530 --> 00:16:30.260
And so this art
installation is kind

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:31.830
of an experiment in empathy.

00:16:31.830 --> 00:16:36.090
Basically the idea is
the state of empathy

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:38.430
seems to allow you to sync.

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:41.230
So what happens if we
measure that syncing process,

00:16:41.230 --> 00:16:44.410
give you visual feedback
almost mechanically,

00:16:44.410 --> 00:16:47.710
and draw your body into
that state of syncing?

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:50.320
Do you then kind of have that
reverse mapping take place

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:52.544
where you then feel empathetic
towards other people.

00:16:52.544 --> 00:16:54.960
It turns out that your body
and your mind are very linked.

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:57.620
So if you force yourself into
a certain physiological state,

00:16:57.620 --> 00:16:59.840
oftentimes the mental
state is connected.

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:02.990
And so that's the idea
of the installation.

00:17:02.990 --> 00:17:06.670
We're kind of riffing on that
as well in India over the fall.

00:17:06.670 --> 00:17:09.829
So basically this is another
big installation, a mural,

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:11.530
that we're going to
do in Dharamsala,

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:14.230
which is where the Dalai
Lama lives in India, and also

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:18.270
in Bombay, which is a huge
city, a bustling metropolis.

00:17:18.270 --> 00:17:20.619
And the idea here is
also very similar.

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:22.160
You can see on the
screen it says,

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:23.630
"There is a path from
your heart to mind,"

00:17:23.630 --> 00:17:24.546
which is a Rumi quote.

00:17:24.546 --> 00:17:27.400
I'm working on this installation
with a really talented artist

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:32.170
named Shilo Shiv Suleman,
who is actually Indian.

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:34.760
And the idea is
basically to allow people

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:37.230
to sync in a public space.

00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:42.120
It's kind of all based around
the idea of sacred spaces

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:43.870
in India, which are
often very public.

00:17:43.870 --> 00:17:44.930
And we're kind of
bringing that back

00:17:44.930 --> 00:17:46.350
with a little bit of technology.

00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:49.880
So the idea is you touch
an illuminated hand that's

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:51.997
kind of set against the wall.

00:17:51.997 --> 00:17:53.580
And there's actually
a sensor embedded

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:54.820
in one of the fingertips.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:57.319
And that sensor measures your
heart rate and your Heart Rate

00:17:57.319 --> 00:17:57.830
Variability.

00:17:57.830 --> 00:18:00.070
So as you start to
relax and breath deeply,

00:18:00.070 --> 00:18:02.810
the entire wall comes
alive with LEDs and lights.

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:05.060
And there's a message that
says, find another partner,

00:18:05.060 --> 00:18:08.394
and another hand that becomes
illuminated across from you.

00:18:08.394 --> 00:18:10.310
So then you have to find
somebody walking down

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:12.500
the street, they have to put
their hand against the wall.

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:13.624
They have to breath deeply.

00:18:13.624 --> 00:18:16.020
When both of you do that
together and the syncing sort

00:18:16.020 --> 00:18:18.450
of happens, then a
hidden message comes out.

00:18:18.450 --> 00:18:20.710
For example, there's a path
from your heart to mind.

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:22.290
It's a fun little
project, but it

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:23.990
is kind of indicative
of the ability

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:26.610
to very quickly use
sensors and a little bit

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:30.200
of signal processing to make
an interactive experience that

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:33.590
allows people to engender
hopefully empathy.

00:18:33.590 --> 00:18:36.350
So we've talked about a couple
devices and a couple art

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:42.070
projects and just general ideas
around meditation and sensors.

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:44.990
And this is something
that I think about a lot.

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:47.870
The idea is, at
least in my own mind,

00:18:47.870 --> 00:18:50.630
to find some sort of device
that I can wear that allows me

00:18:50.630 --> 00:18:54.080
all the time in real time
almost ambiently to be aware

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:58.190
of my own stress levels and to
respond to that appropriately.

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:00.260
So what you need
there is then a sensor

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:02.260
and you need feedback
of some type.

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:06.830
So that feedback
could be visual,

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:08.867
like the HeartMath, that
device with the LEDs

00:19:08.867 --> 00:19:09.700
that go up and down.

00:19:09.700 --> 00:19:11.494
You kind of have to
look at the thing.

00:19:11.494 --> 00:19:13.910
You see it's measuring your
heart rate and your Heart Rate

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:16.580
Variability, and you watch
as the LEDs go up and down.

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:17.830
And that's visual feedback.

00:19:17.830 --> 00:19:19.370
But there are all kinds of
feedback that you could use.

00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:21.000
You can imagine
auditory feedback.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:22.208
We played with that, as well.

00:19:22.208 --> 00:19:24.050
We kind of mocked
together a little sensor

00:19:24.050 --> 00:19:26.510
that goes behind your ear
and kind of beeps at you

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:31.240
all the time when it
recognizes your heart beating.

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:32.664
That's also not very ambient.

00:19:32.664 --> 00:19:34.080
And it's not very
wearable, right?

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:35.680
The ideal device
that kind of does

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:38.170
is, the ideal meditation
technology is probably

00:19:38.170 --> 00:19:42.190
totally invisible, it's
socially acceptable,

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:44.210
and it's wearable
throughout the day.

00:19:44.210 --> 00:19:48.230
And so with those as
design kind of parameters,

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:50.390
we have wrestled a lot
with how to actually make

00:19:50.390 --> 00:19:51.453
this thing work.

00:19:51.453 --> 00:19:53.202
And this is something
that we just started

00:19:53.202 --> 00:19:54.734
working on like a week ago.

00:19:54.734 --> 00:19:56.900
I wanted to show you guys
and get a little feedback.

00:19:56.900 --> 00:20:00.290
It's a little weird but
basically we have these sensors

00:20:00.290 --> 00:20:03.230
and we're like, OK, where on the
body can we measure the signal?

00:20:03.230 --> 00:20:05.170
So what we're
measuring now is HRV.

00:20:05.170 --> 00:20:07.540
It's a very easy
to pick up signal,

00:20:07.540 --> 00:20:09.790
much more so than these
brainwave sensors.

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:13.875
And so we were trying to figure
out exactly how to measure it.

00:20:13.875 --> 00:20:14.870
We looked at the wrist.

00:20:14.870 --> 00:20:17.120
That turned out to be difficult
for different reasons.

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:19.240
It's hard to get a clean
signal from the wrist,

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:21.960
as any of you who bought a
Basis watch probably know.

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:23.790
It's actually not a
trivial thing to do.

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:26.373
I think Google Wear and there's
a whole bunch of other sensors

00:20:26.373 --> 00:20:28.580
that are on the wrist.

00:20:28.580 --> 00:20:31.680
We tried basically
all parts of the body.

00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:34.495
It was pretty ridiculous
seeing us kind of pace

00:20:34.495 --> 00:20:36.050
these sensors all
over the place.

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.500
But this is a process of
trying to find something

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:39.958
in the a space
where you don't know

00:20:39.958 --> 00:20:41.587
what the answer is beforehand.

00:20:41.587 --> 00:20:43.045
And then, eventually--
I apologize.

00:20:43.045 --> 00:20:44.045
This is my friend, Luke.

00:20:44.045 --> 00:20:46.690
He likes to take his
shirt off, god bless him.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:49.827
But this is actually a photo
that we took yesterday.

00:20:49.827 --> 00:20:52.035
And so we kind of, as I
said, just came up with this.

00:20:52.035 --> 00:20:55.455
This is essentially
a belt or strap

00:20:55.455 --> 00:20:57.080
that you wear underneath
your clothing.

00:20:57.080 --> 00:20:58.500
And it's totally invisible.

00:20:58.500 --> 00:21:01.012
And you can kind of
see up in the top right

00:21:01.012 --> 00:21:02.720
that's a diagram for
a patent application

00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:04.130
that we are submitting.

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:06.680
And you can kind of
see it on his chest.

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:08.920
There's a whole bunch of
different vibrating sensors

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:12.280
across a strap that
kind of looks like this.

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:18.287
And so what happens is as your
HRV starts to kind of relax--

00:21:18.287 --> 00:21:19.870
and, again, just to
reiterate one more

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:24.925
time what HRV is because it's a
kind of a hard concept to grok.

00:21:24.925 --> 00:21:27.290
So what you're seeing
in this illustration

00:21:27.290 --> 00:21:29.980
is basically a time
series in the lower

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:32.336
right of heart rate over time.

00:21:32.336 --> 00:21:33.960
And you can see that
it's kind of going

00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:35.160
up and down a little bit.

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:37.060
That was me walking
down the street.

00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:39.580
And then you can see me start
to breathe deeply and relax

00:21:39.580 --> 00:21:42.080
and you can see how kind of the
rhythms start to get really,

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:43.288
really sinusoidal and larger.

00:21:46.290 --> 00:21:49.020
So that large sinusoidal
rhythm, that's HRV.

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:50.120
That's you being relaxed.

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:51.703
And if you don't see
that, then you're

00:21:51.703 --> 00:21:55.390
probably not feeling super calm.

00:21:55.390 --> 00:21:58.263
So essentially what we did
was map that to an array

00:21:58.263 --> 00:21:59.165
of vibrating sensors.

00:22:01.940 --> 00:22:04.080
Similar to the way that
you look at the HeartMath

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:06.360
