00:34:22.699 --> 00:34:25.312
Basically that's like a
very obscure and obtuse way

00:34:25.312 --> 00:34:27.520
of describing just negative
thoughts that kind of run

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:28.630
through your head.

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:29.500
Negative self talk.

00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:31.080
Everybody has that to a degree.

00:34:31.080 --> 00:34:34.320
But oftentimes people that are
depressed can't turn it off.

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:37.560
And to a degree that's a
selective attention problem.

00:34:37.560 --> 00:34:39.449
So if you can train
your attention

00:34:39.449 --> 00:34:41.404
to focus on whatever
it is you like,

00:34:41.404 --> 00:34:43.320
then you can probably
move your attention away

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:46.670
from those thoughts
and towards things

00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:50.550
that are more positive
and beneficial to you.

00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:52.135
So meditation, if
you think of it

00:34:52.135 --> 00:34:53.510
in terms of
attentional training,

00:34:53.510 --> 00:34:55.159
just builds your
attentional muscle.

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:58.150
So I think that is how
it does actually offer

00:34:58.150 --> 00:35:00.300
some benefits with depression.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:02.190
You also mentioned memory loss.

00:35:04.570 --> 00:35:06.739
Memory is like a several
interacting subsystems

00:35:06.739 --> 00:35:07.280
in the brain.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:11.760
So I'm not an expert, so
I'm probably not the person

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:13.040
to talk to you about it.

00:35:13.040 --> 00:35:16.730
But I think it is the case
that intentional training can

00:35:16.730 --> 00:35:18.790
improve your short term memory.

00:35:18.790 --> 00:35:23.605
So not to tout
meditation as a panacea,

00:35:23.605 --> 00:35:24.980
but I think it
does actually help

00:35:24.980 --> 00:35:27.630
to a degree with memory loss
and certainly with depression.

00:35:31.460 --> 00:35:35.100
AUDIENCE: So do you know
the kind of research

00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:38.100
done with people who
selected a group of people,

00:35:38.100 --> 00:35:41.880
for example, with depression
with this training compared

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:46.490
with people who have not
been using this technology

00:35:46.490 --> 00:35:47.519
to see the difference?

00:35:47.519 --> 00:35:48.310
ROHAN DIXIT: Right.

00:35:48.310 --> 00:35:51.210
I think there are probably
a dozen studies that

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:53.880
have looked at that
now in relatively

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:55.304
well controlled ways.

00:35:55.304 --> 00:35:56.970
So usually what you
do is try to compare

00:35:56.970 --> 00:36:00.170
people who learn mindfulness
usually through this course.

00:36:00.170 --> 00:36:02.490
And most hospitals
now, there are maybe

00:36:02.490 --> 00:36:05.080
450 hospitals at this
point around the country

00:36:05.080 --> 00:36:07.190
that offer meditation
as training

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:10.412
for people with anxiety and
depression, also chronic pain.

00:36:10.412 --> 00:36:12.370
And the way they do that
is through this course

00:36:12.370 --> 00:36:15.520
called MBSR, or Mindfulness
Based Stress Reduction.

00:36:15.520 --> 00:36:17.110
It's about an eight week course.

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:21.600
And it kind of guides you
through learning meditation.

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:23.750
And I think that has
been shown to be quite

00:36:23.750 --> 00:36:25.170
efficacious with depression.

00:36:25.170 --> 00:36:26.820
So, if you like, I
can get your email

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:29.075
and send you some of those
studies if that's helpful.

00:36:29.075 --> 00:36:29.616
AUDIENCE: Hi.

