00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:41.850
I don't know what
class of device

00:38:41.850 --> 00:38:44.980
that is, but is that something
you're interested in?

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:46.545
ROHAN DIXIT: It is.

00:38:46.545 --> 00:38:48.670
And, yeah, we have thought
about that a little bit.

00:38:48.670 --> 00:38:52.460
So what you're doing basically
is guiding someone a little.

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:56.050
So over time as you're
listening to the music that's

00:38:56.050 --> 00:38:59.340
being generated
by your breathing,

00:38:59.340 --> 00:39:01.910
if I understand that
device correctly,

00:39:01.910 --> 00:39:05.930
you're sort of building an
association between the music

00:39:05.930 --> 00:39:08.030
and your state of mind.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:10.150
At least your breathing
pattern, right?

00:39:10.150 --> 00:39:16.310
So just like anything else, like
smells of your childhood say,

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:19.320
the ability to smell like fresh
baked chocolate chip cookies

00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:21.080
can remind you of
mom instantaneously

00:39:21.080 --> 00:39:24.540
and a whole suite of memories.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:26.250
So if there's a
certain music that's

00:39:26.250 --> 00:39:28.190
generated when your
breathing is calm

00:39:28.190 --> 00:39:30.840
and then you play that music
back to somebody, most likely

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:34.130
you are able to shift
them into that state.

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:36.910
So by playing with
their current rhythm,

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:38.765
like this is my heart rhythm.

00:39:38.765 --> 00:39:41.140
If I'm feeling it
vibrating against me,

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:43.080
say that's one of
the modes where

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:45.930
that we've built where
kind of the chest strap

00:39:45.930 --> 00:39:48.590
constantly vibrates
at every heart beat.

00:39:48.590 --> 00:39:51.630
It's not super useful, but it is
useful in the sense of guiding,

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:54.210
which is why I built it.

00:39:54.210 --> 00:39:56.240
The idea would be my
heart rate is starting

00:39:56.240 --> 00:39:58.490
to go up a little
bit, maybe too much,

00:39:58.490 --> 00:40:00.760
and the sensor is
reading when my heart

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:03.260
beat is happening and
then sort of slowing it

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:04.500
down a little bit.

00:40:04.500 --> 00:40:07.130
So the feedback that I'm used
to getting on every heartbeat

00:40:07.130 --> 00:40:08.740
is delayed a slight amount.

00:40:08.740 --> 00:40:10.900
And so I feel the
vibration as if I

00:40:10.900 --> 00:40:13.310
had a slightly slower heart
beat than I really do,

00:40:13.310 --> 00:40:16.730
which then guides me towards
a state of a slower heartbeat.

00:40:16.730 --> 00:40:19.760
So there's a ton of interaction
I think that is possible there

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:20.740
through biofeedback.

00:40:20.740 --> 00:40:23.550
And it's funny that it hasn't
really been explored much.

00:40:23.550 --> 00:40:26.440
But I think that's partially
a factor biofeedback becoming

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:30.040
popular in the '70s, promising
a little too much too soon,

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:32.497
and not having the computing
power to really wear

00:40:32.497 --> 00:40:34.330
these things around
with you, which is where

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:35.912
the true benefit I think comes.

00:40:35.912 --> 00:40:38.120
You may be familiar with
these neuro feedback clinics

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:40.060
and biofeedback clinics.

00:40:40.060 --> 00:40:41.390
They're all over the country.

00:40:41.390 --> 00:40:43.840
You basically go to
an office, sit down

00:40:43.840 --> 00:40:46.510
for like an hour and a half
once a week or once a month

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:49.750
and pay $100 or $500
or whatever and try

00:40:49.750 --> 00:40:51.630
to gain some biofeedback
knowledge that way.

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:53.310
But I think now
that the devices are

00:40:53.310 --> 00:40:56.170
much smaller and portable
a lot of these applications

00:40:56.170 --> 00:40:58.560
may become pretty commonplace.

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:01.540
AUDIENCE: You say that people
in long term relationships

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:03.927
can synchronize
their heart rates.

00:41:03.927 --> 00:41:05.510
I thought that was
really interesting.

00:41:05.510 --> 00:41:08.540
And I was wondering if you know
the direction of the causality

00:41:08.540 --> 00:41:09.300
there?

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:11.790
Do people who
spend a lot of time

00:41:11.790 --> 00:41:13.590
together learn to
synchronize their hearts

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:17.600
or do people who are unable to
synchronize their hearts have

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:22.540
relationship trouble and break
up before a year has passed?

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:23.920
ROHAN DIXIT: That's
a fair point.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:26.722
And I don't think
anyone knows the answer.

00:41:26.722 --> 00:41:28.430
But what people did
notice in that study,

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:30.840
in particular, which I
guess is all I can speak to,

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:35.280
is that in general when they
looked at the sort of direction

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:41.290
between the couple in terms
of who was actually syncing

00:41:41.290 --> 00:41:44.400
to the other, I
mean-- you can imagine

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:47.070
that there are sort of like
two metronomes happening--

00:41:47.070 --> 00:41:49.320
and what they found
was that in general one

00:41:49.320 --> 00:41:53.560
member of the couple tended
to sort of see or empathize

00:41:53.560 --> 00:41:55.350
or perceive the
other's oscillation

00:41:55.350 --> 00:41:57.320
and sync to them,
rather than them both

00:41:57.320 --> 00:42:00.954
coming to some sort of
inbetween 50/50 sort of split.

00:42:00.954 --> 00:42:02.370
And in general
what they found was

00:42:02.370 --> 00:42:04.600
that the women in
the relationship

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:06.290
tended to be able
to do that to a much

00:42:06.290 --> 00:42:08.110
greater degree than the men.

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:12.702
So that may have some kind of
insight into your question.

00:42:12.702 --> 00:42:14.160
AUDIENCE: As a
follow up, are there

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.420
any other kinds of relationships
where this happens?

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:17.980
Like could you use
it to predict who

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:21.590
would make compatible co-workers
or astronauts on a mission

00:42:21.590 --> 00:42:23.082
to Mars or something like that?

00:42:23.082 --> 00:42:24.540
ROHAN DIXIT: I
think it's possible.

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:26.847
And the only time I've seen
this study before-- it's

00:42:26.847 --> 00:42:28.680
a pretty recent phenomena
that hasn't really

00:42:28.680 --> 00:42:33.210
been studied much-- was with
I believe family members.

00:42:33.210 --> 00:42:34.460
This was a study out of Spain.

00:42:34.460 --> 00:42:37.219
And people were doing this
fire walking exercise where

00:42:37.219 --> 00:42:39.510
there was a bunch of coals
and one member of the family

00:42:39.510 --> 00:42:42.280
jumps up and kind of
walks across the coals.

00:42:42.280 --> 00:42:44.780
And what they found was that
members of their family,

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:46.200
even watching them
do that, tended

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:49.980
to synchronize with the
HRV of the person who

00:42:49.980 --> 00:42:51.020
was doing the fire walk.

00:42:51.020 --> 00:42:54.760
So it seems to be the case that
in any close relationship kind

00:42:54.760 --> 00:42:55.565
elicits that.

00:42:55.565 --> 00:42:58.470
But I think it's
too early to tell.

00:42:58.470 --> 00:43:01.010
AUDIENCE: So going back
to studying the monks

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:05.310
and going into the meditation.

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:08.800
So how do you know that that's
correlated with brain signals

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:13.767
and not just relaxing the
forehead muscle or something?

00:43:13.767 --> 00:43:16.100
ROHAN DIXIT: How do we know
that what is not correlated?

00:43:16.100 --> 00:43:21.040
AUDIENCE: That going in to
meditation in the signal

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:23.930
that you saw off the
EEG is not correlated

00:43:23.930 --> 00:43:27.215
with relaxing a muscle versus
what's actually coming out

00:43:27.215 --> 00:43:28.220
of the brain?

00:43:28.220 --> 00:43:30.030
ROHAN DIXIT: Sure.

00:43:30.030 --> 00:43:33.420
So EEG has been studied for
like maybe like 100 years now.

00:43:33.420 --> 00:43:37.260
And that is a problem that
every EEG study runs into.

00:43:37.260 --> 00:43:38.760
And so there's kind
of a whole suite

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:41.990
of just standard techniques
to get rid of muscle artifact.

00:43:41.990 --> 00:43:43.990
It looks a lot different
than brainwave activity

00:43:43.990 --> 00:43:45.470
in terms of the
frequency response

00:43:45.470 --> 00:43:47.971
and also the amplitude
of the signal.

00:43:47.971 --> 00:43:49.470
So, in general,
people build in what

00:43:49.470 --> 00:43:51.770
are called artifact
reject algorithms,

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:57.810
just muscle basically signal
rejection that kind of tries

00:43:57.810 --> 00:44:01.060
to see if there is in fact
forehead muscle activity or eye

00:44:01.060 --> 00:44:05.000
blinks or whatever
and reject them.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:06.470
So that's one way
to do it, another

00:44:06.470 --> 00:44:09.791
is-- I think that's probably
a good enough answer.

00:44:09.791 --> 00:44:12.290
There's a ton there actually
in terms of the algorithms that

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:14.397
are used to do that.

00:44:14.397 --> 00:44:17.890
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:21.865 --> 00:44:24.787
--what we can expect from
consumer based hardware.

00:44:24.787 --> 00:44:26.735
Like, you mentioned
the NeuroSky sensors.

00:44:26.735 --> 00:44:30.631
Can we actually get an
interesting signal from that

00:44:30.631 --> 00:44:34.266
or do we have to go with
something much more fancy?

00:44:34.266 --> 00:44:36.390
ROHAN DIXIT: That is a
great question and something

00:44:36.390 --> 00:44:38.500
that we've struggled with a lot.

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:41.967
So the NeuroSky is probably
the cheapest EEG device

00:44:41.967 --> 00:44:43.050
that's ever been released.

00:44:43.050 --> 00:44:44.560
It's a single sensor.

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:47.112
And it's pretty noisy.

00:44:47.112 --> 00:44:48.820
I mean, coming from
a research background

00:44:48.820 --> 00:44:52.040
where we use higher quality
research grade rather

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:55.940
than clinical grade EEG, the
signal is almost night and day.

00:44:55.940 --> 00:44:59.960
To get any kind of useful
signal out of for example

00:44:59.960 --> 00:45:02.965
a NeuroSky is an incredible
feat of signal processing

00:45:02.965 --> 00:45:03.840
and machine learning.

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:07.700
And we're helped by the fact
that in meditation usually

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:09.860
your eyes are closed
and you're pretty still.

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:12.520
So basically what
we have found is

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:16.710
a kind of subset of
what you can measure

00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:18.460
in terms of brain
activity and an activity

00:45:18.460 --> 00:45:20.043
that allows you to
do that pretty well

00:45:20.043 --> 00:45:22.930
and get a relatively
good signal.

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:25.360
There's a device
coming out pretty soon

00:45:25.360 --> 00:45:28.112
called the Muse which I
think is just now fulfilling

00:45:28.112 --> 00:45:28.820
their pre-orders.

00:45:28.820 --> 00:45:31.160
And that's a much more
high quality device.

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:36.340
I think it's five sensors
or six rather than just one.

00:45:36.340 --> 00:45:40.009
But I think for at least for
the foreseeable short term

00:45:40.009 --> 00:45:41.550
future, a lot of
these consumer grade

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:44.090
EEG devices are
going to be much less

00:45:44.090 --> 00:45:49.650
high quality than your passive
electrode kind of clinical EEG.

00:45:49.650 --> 00:45:50.150
All right.

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:51.420
Thank you very much.

00:45:51.420 --> 00:45:54.770
[APPLAUSE]

